#2

From this, we see that 3.24% of the flights are redeye flights.

flights <- flights %>%
  mutate(dep_time_cat = cut(dep_time,
                            breaks = c(0, 600, 1200, 1800, 2400),
                            labels = c("Early Morn", "Morning", 
                                       "Afternoon", "Evening")))
flights %>%
  filter(!is.na(dep_time_cat)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = dep_time_cat)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(x = "Departure Time", title = "Categorical Departure Time")
flights <- flights %>%
  mutate(arr_time_cat = cut(arr_time,
                            breaks = c(0, 600, 1200, 1800, 2400),
                            labels = c("Early Morn", "Morning", 
                                       "Afternoon", "Evening")))
flights %>%
  filter(!is.na(arr_time_cat)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = arr_time_cat)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(x = "Arrival Time", title = "Categorical Arrival Time")
flights <- flights %>%
  mutate(redeye = ifelse((dep_time_cat == "Afternoon" | dep_time_cat == "Evening") & 
                          (arr_time_cat == "Early Morn" | arr_time_cat == "Morning"), 
                         TRUE, FALSE))
flights %>%
  summarize(prop_redeye = mean(redeye, na.rm = T))
# A tibble: 1 Ã 1
  prop_redeye
        <dbl>
1      0.0324

Pasting together these 5 variables creates a unique combination for all but 3 of the total observations. The reason these ones are duplicated is because all of these occurred at 1am on November 3, which is the date and time that DST ended. Therefore, 1am occurred 2x as the clocks switched times.

Temperature and wind speed seem to have a normal(ish) distribution. Wind gust, precipitation, and visibility are all skewed.

#9

First, I created a categorical variable for precipitation: TRUE if there was any rain/snow, FALSE if it was dry. I found that 6.86% of the flights were recorded to have some precipitation at the time of departure, and it looks like the average delay was higher for the ânot dryâ group. However, when I plotted these with boxplots, I found that the highest delays werenât part of the ânot dryâ group, and, to the naked eye, the difference in the means doesnât look like a lot. Therefore, precipitation doesnât seem to be the sole cause of the worst delays. I did a similar thing to see if wind gust affected delays; the means between those with any wind gust and those with none were very similar. Boxplots showed that the highest delays didnât have any wind gust. Therefore, wind gust also doesnât seem to be the cause of the worst delays. I repeated this one more time with a fog categorical variable. The average delay for the âfogâ group did seem to be higher than that of the âclearâ group, but overall it doesnât look like fog was the cause of the worst delays either.

Even though rain, wind, and fog donât seem to individually cause the worst delays, it is possible a combination of one or more of these weather conditions causes the worst delays. I decided to subset the data to focus on flights determined to be ânot dryâ and examined how delays were affected by wind speed and visibility within this group. It does appear, despite the relationship not being very strong, that delays do increase when there is precipitation and high wind speeds. There may also be increased delays when there is precipitation and low visibility, although this relationship looks less strong., likely because there are significantly fewer data points for those conditions.
